      "text": "A recent discussion on the wikipedia research list. [https://lists.wikimedia.org/hyperkitty/list/wiki-research-l@lists.wikimedia.org/thread/VCVRL5J3WDSIFYRMQE5IRXF3QESY46PG/ list]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "737391d848964ee3",
      "text": "> I was wondering if folks who are doing (or are interested in) research about Wikipedia might like to share texts that they feel best describe the general research frameworks they use or might like to use."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3f1b678355d627ab",
      "text": "Some authors have tried to make use of systems theory, but this is not\nwhat I would recommend.\nIt all depends what your research is about, so the framework would\ncome from media science? computer science? social science?\nlinguistics? etc."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fd4cd60d4f816683",
      "text": "\nA book I that I found useful for my thought process was this one:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "04d61b963c956ded",
      "text": "\nJerome Kagan: The Three Cultures. Natural Sciences, Social Sciences,\nand the Humanities in the 21st Century. Cambridge University Press,\nCambridge et.al. 2009."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a0cb5d978dbc68cb",
      "text": "\nIt reminded me of the different approaches that are common in\ndifferent disciplines."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2aef35f350701568",
      "text": "\nIn \"Wikis und die Wikipedia verstehen\" I have written some lines about\nit, here in a rough semi-automatic translation. See below. \nZiko"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9c77f8ae939aa46e",
      "text": "\n\nKagan speaks of \"three cultures\" that offer different approaches to\nreality. The three cultures differ in which main questions are asked\nin a science, which sources are collected, and what control one has\nover the circumstances under which evidence is collected, to what\ndegree one generalizes, to what extent one takes into account\nhistorical phenomena, and what importance one attaches to ethical\nvalues. Kagan suspects that humanists and social scientists are more\nsimilar to each other in their ideas and methods than they are to the\nnatural scientists (Kagan 2009: 2/3). If necessary, one can speak of a\nsocio-cultural approach."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e1a879564a9324cf",
      "text": "\nNatural scientists, according to Kagan, are concerned with predicting\nand explaining natural phenomena. One observes the material in a\ncontrolled way in experiments and works in both small and large\ngroups. Scholars in the Humanities are interested in how people react\nto events and what meaning they ascribe to an experience. Historical\ncircumstances and the influence of the ethical are of the highest\nimportance to them. They usually work alone and delight in\n\"semantically coherent arguments described in elegant prose.\" Social\nscientists are concerned with the predictability and explanation of\nhuman behavior (ibid.: 4/5)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "007c5303976d2943",
      "text": "\nIn this book, therefore, we distinguish between the following three\nlevels or dimensions in which wiki-related phenomena take place or can\nbe described."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "23b4c9d6b659877b",
      "text": "\n- The technical dimension refers to the technical and scientific\nsubjects, including subjects from computer science and mathematics.\nOne focus is the wiki as a technical medium including user accounts\nand pages."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7eaaa79e4527e87a",
      "text": "- The cultural dimension deals with typical humanities issues,\nespecially with regard to the wiki content."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4bec116b964ffdb0",
      "text": "- The (human) social dimension is concerned with the social relations\nbetween the actors. This communicative dimension is to be understood\ncomprehensively, and it deals not only with questions of the actual\nsocial sciences, but also of law and politics.\n\n"
    }
